-- allium: 3
-- turbo_kv_residual_window.allium

-- Scope: residual window KV-cache improvement — keep the most
-- recent N tokens in fp16 uncompressed, quantise only the older
-- tail. Composes on top of the core TurboQuant specs
-- (turbo-kv-4b.allium, turbo-kv-3b.allium).
--
-- Citable sources:
--
--   [PAPER]       Zandieh et al., arxiv 2504.19874. Paper does
--                 not model a residual window — it treats the full
--                 sequence as a single quantisation batch.
--
--   [TONBI-V3]    tonbistudio/turboquant-pytorch compressors_v3.py.
--                 Introduces residual_window as a core V3 concept.
--                 Measured evidence (README needle-in-haystack on
--                 Llama 3.2):
--                   K4/V4 rw=128:  EXACT at 2K and 4K ctx
--                   K4/V4 rw=0:    MISS (garbage output)
--                   K4/V2 rw=0:    MISS
--                 The rw=0 → MISS result is the critical evidence:
--                 symmetric 4-bit quantisation without a residual
--                 window fails the most basic retrieval task. The
--                 residual window is not a minor optimisation; it
--                 is load-bearing for 4-bit-and-below quality.
--                 README: "What doesn't work: 3-4 bit compression
--                 without a residual window produces garbage, same
--                 as V2."
--
--   [QUANT.CPP]   Does NOT implement a residual window. Our
--                 llama.cpp port inherits this gap. The port's
--                 current 4-bit symmetric KV matches the
--                 [TONBI-V3] K4/V4 rw=0 failing configuration —
--                 the 9B +0.23 PPL observation is consistent with
--                 this being a driver.
--
-- Goal: specify a residual_window parameter that, when > 0,
-- causes the most recent `residual_window` tokens to bypass
-- quantisation and remain in fp16. All older tokens are
-- quantised per the core TurboQuant spec. Attention reads the
-- concatenation of (quantised tail + fp16 window).
--
-- Includes: rolling-window maintenance, tail quantisation trigger,
-- read-time concatenation of fp16 + quantised.
-- Excludes: per-layer window-size overrides (layer-adaptive is a
-- separate spec), asymmetric K/V bit widths (separate spec).

-- ============================================================
-- External entities
-- ============================================================

external entity Tensor {
    data: Set<Decimal>
    count: Integer
}

-- The KV-cache is organised as a sequence of rows, one per token
-- position per head. Recent rows live in fp16; older rows are
-- quantised via turbo-kv-4b.allium's QuantizeHead (or 3b).
external entity FloatRow {
    data: Set<Decimal>
    count: Integer
    position: Integer
}

external entity QuantizedHead {
    norm: Decimal
    inv_std: Decimal
    indices: Set<Integer>
}

-- ============================================================
-- Config
-- ============================================================

config {
    -- Size of the rolling fp16 tail. [TONBI-V3] default is 128.
    -- Larger window → better recent-token attention fidelity at
    -- the cost of compression ratio; smaller window → more
    -- compression at the cost of tail-quality. [TONBI-V3] README
    -- measurements use rw=128 and report EXACT needle-retrieval
    -- at 2K and 4K contexts on Llama 3.2.
    residual_window: Integer = 128

    -- A context length at or below which the residual window
    -- subsumes the whole sequence (i.e. no quantisation happens).
    -- At seq_len ≤ residual_window the entire cache is fp16.
    -- This matches [TONBI-V3] compress_kv behaviour: "If S <= rw,
    -- keep everything in fp16".
    min_seq_for_quantisation: Integer = 129
}

-- ============================================================
-- Open questions
-- ============================================================

open question "Residual window size tuning: [TONBI-V3] defaults to 128 and reports it as the knee of the quality curve at model scales around 3B. Larger models or head_dim=256 configurations (Qwen3.5 9B) may need a larger window; smaller models may tolerate less. No public measurement campaign at our target sizes."

open question "Sliding vs fixed-start window: [TONBI-V3] implements the rolling-tail semantics (most recent N tokens in fp16, rest quantised). An alternative would be a fixed initial-tokens window (first N tokens in fp16 for the attention-sink / first-few-tokens phenomenon literature). This spec models the rolling-tail variant only."

open question "Interaction with quant.cpp Variant F multi-block split: the core spec (turbo-kv-4b.allium) inherits the per-128-element sub-block split. The residual window acts at the TOKEN level (rows); it is orthogonal to the within-row quantisation granularity. Composition should be clean, but the interaction has not been empirically tested."

-- ============================================================
-- Composite rules
-- ============================================================

-- Incremental write (seq_len ≤ residual_window): the whole
-- sequence fits in the fp16 window. No quantisation happens;
-- the row is appended as fp16.
rule AppendRowWithinWindow {
    when: AppendRow(row, seq_len)

    requires: row.count > 0
    requires: seq_len <= config.residual_window

    ensures: FloatRow.created(
        data: row.data,
        count: row.count,
        position: seq_len
    )
}

-- Incremental write (seq_len > residual_window): the window
-- is full, so the oldest fp16 row (at position
-- seq_len - residual_window - 1) is quantised via the core
-- spec's QuantizeHead rule and moved to the quantised tail.
-- The new row is appended as fp16 at the head of the window.
--
-- This matches [TONBI-V3] compress_kv's split semantics: older
-- than `split_at = S - rw` is compressed, rest is fp16.
rule AppendRowWithEviction {
    when: AppendRow(row, seq_len)

    requires: row.count > 0
    requires: seq_len > config.residual_window

    let evicted_row = oldest_fp16_row_before_append(row, seq_len, config.residual_window)
    let quantised = QuantizeHead(evicted_row, config.seed)

    ensures: FloatRow.created(
        data: row.data,
        count: row.count,
        position: seq_len
    )
    -- QuantizeHead's own ensures clause (from the core spec)
    -- creates the QuantizedHead entity for the evicted row.
}

-- Read (seq_len ≤ residual_window): whole sequence is in the
-- fp16 window. Attention reads only the fp16 range.
rule ReadKVShortSequence {
    when: ReadKVForAttention(query_position, seq_len)

    requires: seq_len > 0
    requires: seq_len <= config.residual_window

    let fp16_range = positions(0, seq_len)

    ensures: result = attention_read_fp16(fp16_range)
}

-- Read (seq_len > residual_window): attention reads the
-- quantised tail [0, seq_len - residual_window) plus the fp16
-- window [seq_len - residual_window, seq_len).
rule ReadKVLongSequence {
    when: ReadKVForAttention(query_position, seq_len)

    requires: seq_len > 0
    requires: seq_len > config.residual_window

    let quantised_range = positions(0, seq_len - config.residual_window)
    let fp16_range = positions(seq_len - config.residual_window, seq_len)

    ensures: result = attention_read_mixed(quantised_range, fp16_range)
}

-- ============================================================
-- Invariants
-- ============================================================

-- At any point, the quantised tail plus the fp16 window covers
-- the whole sequence with no overlap and no gap.
invariant CoverageCompleteNoOverlap {
    for q in ActiveQueries:
        let fp16_size = min(q.seq_len, config.residual_window)
        let quant_size = max(0, q.seq_len - config.residual_window)
        fp16_size + quant_size = q.seq_len
}

-- Recent tokens must be fp16 — no lossy compression on the N
-- most recent positions.
invariant RecentTokensLossless {
    for q in ActiveQueries:
        for position in recent_positions(q, config.residual_window):
            position_representation(q, position) = "fp16"
}

-- Default config bound — 0 would match our port's current state
-- (no residual window). Must be ≥ 0.
invariant ResidualWindowNonNegative {
    config.residual_window >= 0
}

-- ============================================================
-- Implementation notes
-- ============================================================

-- The [TONBI-V3] reference implementation is in
-- tonbistudio/turboquant-pytorch/turboquant/compressors_v3.py
-- (class TurboQuantV3, method compress_kv). Their compressed
-- output is a dict with keys: "compressed" (quantised tail),
-- "fp16" (recent window), "shape", "split_at" (first quantised
-- index).
--
-- Our llama.cpp port has NO residual window today; the port's
-- KV cache is fully quantised from position 0. Adopting this
-- improvement requires: a second fp16 buffer for the window,
-- a rolling-write path that quantises the evicted row, and an
-- attention-read path that does one pass over the quantised
-- tail and one over the fp16 window then concatenates.
--
-- Approximate implementation cost: moderate. The rolling-window
-- machinery is a scheduler concern (where the fp16 and
-- quantised buffers are allocated and how eviction is timed),
-- not a numerics concern. Attention dispatch needs to handle
-- a mixed-precision KV but that's a one-of configuration, not
-- per-call branching.
